    descriptionEn: 'On October 25, 1415, King Henry V of England led about 6,000 exhausted and disease-ridden men (roughly 5,000 of them longbowmen) against a French force of 20,000-30,000 at Agincourt in northern France. Fighting took place on a muddy field flanked by woods that Henry used to constrain French cavalry deployment. As armored French knights struggled through the mud, English longbowmen unleashed devastating volleys, killing men and horses alike and forcing panicked cavalry into narrow killing zones. The flower of French nobility was annihilated: 7,000-10,000 French dead against a few hundred English casualties. The victory gave Henry V control of much of northern France and the French succession through the Treaty of Troyes. Agincourt remains one of the most celebrated victories in English military history.',
