    descriptionEn: 'In 1848, an unprecedented wave of revolution swept continental Europe. In February, the Paris revolution overthrew Louis-Philippe\'s July Monarchy, establishing the Second Republic. In March, Vienna and Berlin erupted; Metternich was forced to resign and flee to London; Prussia\'s Frederick William IV was compelled to promise a constitution. That same month, national independence movements erupted in Hungary, the Italian states, and Bohemia. Marx and Engels published "The Communist Manifesto." Yet the revolutionary coalition quickly fractured between liberals and radicals, and between advocates of a greater versus lesser German unification. By the summer of 1849, reactionary forces had gradually suppressed the revolutions across Europe. Though it failed on the surface, 1848 irreversibly brought democratic, liberal, and nationalist ideas into the European political mainstream. Slavery was abolished in French colonies.',
